Below is a quick‑start tutorial that shows how to build a **simple web scraper** for the Hacker News “new” page (`https://news.ycombinator.com/news`) using **Playwright**.  
The tutorial assumes you’re working in a Node.js environment (any recent LTS is fine) and that you want to run a standalone script – not a Playwright test.

---

## 1. Why Playwright?

Playwright is a modern browser automation library that supports Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit in a single API.  
Key reasons to pick it for scraping:

| Feature | Why it matters for scraping |
|---------|-----------------------------|
| **Headless & Headful** | Run without a UI (headless) for speed, or see what’s happening (headful). |
| **Automatic waits** | `page.locator()` and `expect()` automatically wait for elements to be ready, cutting down on flaky code. |
| **Multiple browsers** | Test against Chrome, Firefox, Safari with one script. |
| **Rich selectors** | CSS selectors, text selectors, XPath, etc. |
| **Easy install & run** | `npx playwright install` pulls browsers automatically. |

---

## 2. Project setup

```bash
# 1️⃣ Create a new folder (if you don't have one)
mkdir hn-scraper && cd hn-scraper

# 2️⃣ Initialise npm
npm init -y

# 3️⃣ Install Playwright
npm i playwright

# 4️⃣ (Optional) Install TypeScript for type safety
npm i -D typescript @types/node

# 5️⃣ Create tsconfig.json (if using TS)
npx tsc --init
```

> **Tip:** If you don’t want TypeScript, just skip step 4/5 and write plain JavaScript (`.js` files).  

---

## 3. The scraper – `scrape.js`

Create a file `scrape.js` (or `scrape.ts` if you’re using TS).  
The script performs the following:

1. Launches a browser (Chromium by default).  
2. Navigates to the Hacker News “new” page.  
3. Waits for the list of stories to load.  
4. Extracts the title, URL, and the sub‑text (score, author, age, comments).  
5. Prints a nicely formatted table to the console.

```js
// scrape.js
// 1️⃣ Import the Playwright API
const { chromium } = require('playwright');

// 2️⃣ Async IIFE to allow await at top level
(async () => {
  // 3️⃣ Launch browser (headless by default)
  const browser = await chromium.launch();
  const context = await browser.newContext();

  // 4️⃣ Create a new page/tab
  const page = await context.newPage();

  // 5️⃣ Navigate to HN “new” page
  await page.goto('https://news.ycombinator.com/news', { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });

  // 6️⃣ Wait for the story rows to appear
  await page.waitForSelector('tr.athing');

  // 7️⃣ Grab all story rows (the ones with class “athing”)
  const stories = await page.$$eval('tr.athing', rows => {
    return rows.map(row => {
      // The title is inside <a class="storylink">
      const titleLink = row.querySelector('a.storylink');
      const title = titleLink ? titleLink.innerText.trim() : '';
      const url = titleLink ? titleLink.href : '';

      // The sub‑text is the next sibling row (class="subtext")
      const subtextRow = row.nextElementSibling;
      const subtext = subtextRow ? subtextRow.innerText.trim() : '';

      return { title, url, subtext };
    });
  });

  // 8️⃣ Print results
  console.log(`Found ${stories.length} stories on Hacker News:\n`);
  stories.forEach((s, idx) => {
    console.log(`${idx + 1}. ${s.title}`);
    console.log(`   URL   : ${s.url}`);
    console.log(`   Info  : ${s.subtext}\n`);
  });

  // 9️⃣ Clean up
  await browser.close();
})();
```

### What the script does in detail

| Step | Code snippet | Explanation |
|------|--------------|-------------|
| 1 | `const { chromium } = require('playwright');` | Pulls the Chromium launcher from Playwright. |
| 5 | `await page.goto(..., { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });` | Loads the page and waits until the DOM is ready. |
| 6 | `await page.waitForSelector('tr.athing');` | Guarantees that at least one story row exists before proceeding. |
| 7 | `page.$$eval('tr.athing', ...)` | Runs a function in the page context that maps over every story row. |
| 7‑inside | `row.querySelector('a.storylink')` | Extracts the link element containing the title. |
| 7‑inside | `row.nextElementSibling` | The sub‑text row sits immediately after the title row. |
| 8 | `console.log(...)` | Pretty‑prints the results. |

---

## 4. Run the script

```bash
node scrape.js
```

You should see output similar to:

```
Found 30 stories on Hacker News:

1. An interesting blog post
   URL   : https://example.com/interesting
   Info  : 123 points by alice | 45 comments

2. Another headline
   URL   : https://another.com
   Info  : 78 points by bob | 12 comments

...
```

---

## 5. Going further (optional)

| Feature | How to add it |
|---------|--------------|
| **Headful mode** | `await chromium.launch({ headless: false })` |
| **Save to JSON** | `fs.writeFileSync('hn.json', JSON.stringify(stories, null, 2));` |
| **Pagination** | After scraping, click the “More” link (`a[rel="next"]`) and repeat. |
| **Parallel scraping** | Launch multiple contexts or pages with `browser.newContext()` and `context.newPage()` concurrently. |
| **Error handling** | Wrap the main block in `try/catch` and use `finally` to close the browser. |
| **TypeScript** | Rename file to `scrape.ts`, add types, and compile with `tsc`. |

---

## 6. Quick reference to Playwright docs

| Topic | Docs URL |
|-------|----------|
| Intro & installation | https://playwright.dev/docs/intro |
| API reference | https://playwright.dev/docs/api/class-page |
| Locators & selectors | https://playwright.dev/docs/locators |
| Browser launch options | https://playwright.dev/docs/api/class-browser |
| Running scripts | https://playwright.dev/docs/test-runners#run-scripts-directly |

Feel free to dive deeper into any of those sections for more advanced scraping techniques (e.g., handling infinite scroll, waiting for network idle, dealing with dynamic content).

---

**That’s it!**  
You now have a fully functional, Playwright‑based scraper that pulls the latest stories from Hacker News. Happy scraping!
